        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nAt thirteen, he sat at the dining table, his father\u2019s engineering blueprints spread under his math textbook. From the living room, he heard his mother humming as she draped a bolt of brilliant Persian brocade over their sensible Italian sofa. The intricate, shimmering gold thread against the deep blue silk seemed to change the energy of the entire house. In that moment, the rigid lines of geometry on his page felt meaningless. He understood, viscerally, that a single beautiful object could tell a more compelling story than any equation.\n\n2.\nHe was eighteen, fresh from San Jose and standing on a street corner in Hayes Valley for the first time. A man walked past in a perfectly tailored linen suit paired with worn-in sneakers, a look of effortless, personal defiance. It was as if a sketch from one of Kian\u2019s hidden notebooks had come to life. The sight struck him with the force of a revelation. This city didn't just tolerate style; it celebrated it as a form of identity. He felt a profound, calming sense of belonging, a quiet click of a lock turning.\n\n3.\nThe breaking point, at 29, was a Tuesday in the stockroom. He was surrounded by cardboard boxes holding five thousand units of the exact same machine-made, beige V-neck sweater. The sheer soullessness of the pile, the absence of any passion or craft, was suffocating. He stared at the plastic-wrapped stacks and realized he wasn't just managing inventory; he was burying his own creativity under it. Quitting his assistant manager job that Friday wasn't a choice, but a necessary act of self-preservation.\n\n4.\nAbout four years ago, a longtime customer came into the boutique, devastated after a layoff. He looked defeated. Kian spent an hour with him, not just selling clothes, but rebuilding a silhouette. He found a sharp, structured jacket and a soft cashmere knit that made the man stand taller. Seeing the shift in his customer\u2019s posture in the mirror\u2014a flicker of his old confidence returning\u2014was more rewarding than any sales goal. It solidified his belief that his work wasn't frivolous; it was about honoring the person inside the clothes.\n\n5.\nLast year, sitting in the quiet of his Inner Richmond apartment after the breakup, he traced the patterns on a pillow his mother had given him. The relationship had ended over differing dreams\u2014his singular focus on an imagined shop versus a desire for shared, stable comforts. The silence felt vast and terrifying, but also clean. He suddenly saw the empty space not as a loss, but as the first real, tangible square footage for his dream. The grief was real, but so was the startling, clarifying freedom."
